     1	# `rhei run` TUI and Transition Journal
     2	
     3	This document specifies a live visualization layer for parallel agent execution under `rhei run` and the persistent transition journal that backs it. The design extracts a reusable frontend crate (`rhei-tui`) that can be driven by any parallel `rhei` subcommand — not only `rhei run` — and preserves the current plain-stdout behavior for non-interactive use.
     4	
     5	For the surrounding `rhei run` behavior see [Rhei Usage](rhei-usage.spec.md) and [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md).
     6	
     7	## Goals
     8	
     9	1. **Visualize parallel agent activity.** When `rhei run --parallel N` is running in an interactive terminal, the user sees a live view of up to N agents, each with its task id, current state, elapsed time, and a short tail of its log.
    10	2. **Keep a light transition log.** Each state transition produces exactly one line in a persistent journal. Every line carries both the transition (`from → to`) and the absolute path to the detailed log for that state.
    11	3. **Remain CI-friendly.** When stdout is not a TTY (piped, redirected, CI runners), `rhei run` produces the same line-oriented output as today. The journal is written identically in both modes.
    12	4. **Be reusable.** Any future parallel `rhei` subcommand reuses the same event surface and frontend.
    13	
    14	## Non-Goals
    15	
    16	- Replacing the current plain-stdout mode. The TUI is an additional view, not a replacement.
    17	- Streaming agent stdout to a central log aggregator. Agents continue to write per-task log files; the TUI tails those files.
    18	- Remote visualization. The TUI renders to the local terminal only.
    19	
    20	## Architecture
    21	
    22	A single `rhei run` process decomposes into three concerns:
    23	
    24	1. **Execution engine** — the existing `run_agent_mode` / `run_callback_mode` logic, refactored to emit events through an `EventSink` instead of calling `println!` directly.
    25	2. **Sinks** — implementations of `EventSink` that consume events. The engine always writes through a `Tee` that fans out to a journal sink and a frontend sink.
    26	3. **Frontend** — either a plain stdout writer (non-TTY) or a TUI renderer (TTY). Frontend selection is decided once at startup based on `stdout.is_terminal()`, with `--tui` and `--no-tui` overrides.
    27	
    28	```
    29	engine ──► Tee ──┬──► JournalSink   (runtime/transitions.log, always on)
    30	                 └──► FrontendSink  (TuiSink if TTY, else StdoutSink)
    31	```
    32	
    33	Slot-oriented events (see below) mean the renderer updates exactly one tile per event. The engine assigns a slot index when it spawns an agent and releases it when the agent exits.
    34	
    35	### Event Surface
    36	
    37	```rust
    38	// crates/rhei-tui/src/event.rs
    39	pub enum RunEvent {
    40	    RunStarted    { workspace: PathBuf, parallel: u8, total_tasks: usize },
    41	    PassStarted   { pass: u32, ready: Vec<TaskId> },
    42	    SlotAssigned  { slot: u8, task: TaskId, from: StateName, to: StateName,
    43	                    log_path: PathBuf, started_at: Instant },
    44	    SlotReleased  { slot: u8, task: TaskId, outcome: TaskOutcome,
    45	                    finished_at: Instant },
    46	    AgentOutput   { slot: u8, task: TaskId, stream: AgentStream,
    47	                    line: String, wall_clock: SystemTime },
    48	    PassEnded     { pass: u32, progressed: bool },
    49	    RunFinished   { summary: RunSummary },
    50	}
    51	
    52	pub enum AgentStream { Stdout, Stderr }
    53	pub enum TaskOutcome { Completed, Failed(String), Cancelled, TimedOut }
    54	
    55	pub trait EventSink: Send + Sync {
    56	    fn emit(&self, event: RunEvent);
    57	}
    58	```
    59	
    60	`SlotAssigned` is emitted at spawn time; `SlotReleased` is emitted when the spawned agent or program exits. Both events carry the slot index so the renderer can update the right tile without reconciliation.
    61	
    62	`AgentOutput` is emitted for live agent subprocess traffic after the slot is assigned and before it is released. The event is line-oriented and identifies stdout vs stderr with `AgentStream`. Lines are ordered per stream; interleaving between stdout and stderr is best-effort because the two streams are read concurrently. The per-task log file remains the complete durable transcript.
    63	
    64	`Tee` is a composite sink implementing `EventSink` by forwarding each event to a fixed list of inner sinks.
    65	
    66	### Live Agent Traffic
    67	
    68	`rhei run` intercepts stdout and stderr for built-in autonomous agents through a shared subprocess capture path:
    69	
    70	| Agent id | Prompt transport | Output capture |
    71	|----------|------------------|----------------|
    72	| `claude-code` | `-p <prompt>` | stdout/stderr are piped, logged, and emitted as `AgentOutput` |
    73	| `codex` | stdin, followed by `--` separator | stdout/stderr are piped, logged, and emitted as `AgentOutput` |
    74	| `pi` | `-p <prompt>` | stdout/stderr are piped, logged, and emitted as `AgentOutput` |
    75	
    76	Agent-specific behavior belongs only to command construction and prompt delivery. Traffic interception is transport-agnostic once the child process has been spawned.
    77	
    78	The TUI keeps a bounded recent traffic buffer per active slot and may drop display events if the render channel is full. Dropped display events do not affect `runtime/logs/*`: the log writer remains the durable sink and receives every captured line unless the filesystem write itself fails. Long or control-sequence-heavy lines may be sanitized and truncated for rendering, but the log preserves the raw bytes captured from the subprocess stream.
    79	
    80	### Sink Implementations
    81	
    82	- **`JournalSink`** — opens `runtime/transitions.log` in append mode at construction and writes one line per `SlotAssigned` and one line per `SlotReleased`. Line format is fixed-column and tail-friendly (see below). The journal is always written, in every mode.
    83	- **`StdoutSink`** — reproduces the current `println!` output exactly. It is the default frontend when stdout is not a TTY.
    84	- **`TuiSink`** — owns a bounded `crossbeam_channel` and a render thread. It implements `EventSink` by pushing events onto the channel; the render thread consumes events and updates the UI.
    85	
    86	### Frontend Selection
    87	
    88	At the entry of `run_plan`, the frontend is decided once:
    89	
    90	| Condition                                         | Frontend   |
    91	|--------------------------------------------------|------------|
    92	| `--no-tui`, or `stdout` is not a TTY              | StdoutSink |
    93	| `--tui`, regardless of TTY detection              | TuiSink    |
    94	| Default: `stdout.is_terminal()` is true            | TuiSink    |
    95	
    96	Auto-detection uses `std::io::IsTerminal`. The `--tui` override exists for edge cases where detection is wrong (nested shells, certain tmux configurations). The `--no-tui` override is for scripted demos and debugging.
    97	
    98	### Layout Rules (TuiSink)
    99	
   100	The renderer allocates a fixed pool of N slots matching `--parallel N`. Slots are reused as tasks complete — the grid does not grow unbounded.
   101	
   102	| N    | Terminal constraint                | Layout                                    |
   103	|------|------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|
   104	| 1    | any                                | Single full-width pane with log tail      |
   105	| 2–4  | rows-per-tile ≥ 6                  | 2×2 grid with log tail                    |
   106	| 5–9  | rows-per-tile ≥ 6                  | 3×3 grid, shorter tiles, log tail         |
   107	| any  | rows-per-tile < 6                  | Compact list: one row per slot, no tail   |
   108	| ≥ 10 | any                                | Compact list mode                         |
   109	
   110	A persistent journal pane at the bottom shows the most recent transitions regardless of mode. Layout is recomputed on terminal resize (`crossterm::event::Event::Resize`).
   111	
   112	Each tile shows:
   113	- task id + short title
   114	- current state (the `to` field of its `SlotAssigned` event)
   115	- elapsed time (updated once per second)
   116	- last 5 lines of the log file at `log_path`, tailed via the `notify` crate with a bounded 50-line ring buffer
   117	
   118	Idle slots show `— idle —`.
   119	
   120	### Journal Format
   121	
   122	`runtime/transitions.log` is a UTF-8, append-only, newline-delimited text file. Each line is one event. Columns are space-separated; columns 1–3 are fixed-width, column 4 is a path, and optional trailing fields are comma-separated key=value pairs.
   123	
   124	```
   125	2026-04-21T14:03:22Z  task-042  draft→pending           runtime/logs/task-042-pending.log
   126	2026-04-21T14:03:22Z  task-042  pending→agent-review    runtime/logs/task-042-agent-review.log
   127	2026-04-21T14:07:11Z  task-042  agent-review→completed  runtime/logs/task-042-agent-review.log  exit=0,duration=3m49s
   128	```
   129	
   130	Rules:
   131	- Timestamps are UTC, RFC 3339, second precision.
   132	- The transition column uses the UTF-8 arrow `→` (U+2192).
   133	- Paths are workspace-relative if inside the workspace, otherwise absolute.
   134	- Trailing metadata is only added on `SlotReleased` events (`exit`, `duration`, `outcome`).
   135	- The file is safe to `tail -f` from other shells while `rhei run` is active.
   136	
   137	A `SlotAssigned` produces one line; its paired `SlotReleased` produces a second line on the same state (recording exit status and duration). For multi-invocation states (`all_targets`), each invocation is a distinct pair of lines with the target suffix visible in the log path.
   138	
   139	### Failure Modes
   140	
   141	- **Panic in the execution engine** — a panic hook registered by `TuiSink` calls `ratatui::restore()` before re-raising, so the terminal is never left in raw mode.
   142	- **Ctrl+C** — because the TUI runs the terminal in raw mode, Ctrl+C arrives as a key event rather than an automatic `SIGINT`. `TuiSink` restores the terminal, explicitly re-raises `SIGINT` for the process, and then exits its render loop.
   143	- **Terminal too small for any tile** — auto-degrade to compact list mode; never crash.
   144	- **Slow log file growth** — the log tailer uses a bounded 50-line ring buffer and never blocks the engine thread.
   145	- **Journal write failure** — log a warning to stderr and continue; journal errors never abort a run.
   146	
   147	### Reuse
   148	
   149	`rhei-tui` is a standalone crate with no dependency on `rhei-cli`. Any future subcommand that fans out to a worker pool constructs:
   150	
   151	```rust
   152	rhei_tui::run_with_frontend(
   153	    engine_fn,
   154	    RunParams { parallel, workspace_root, total_tasks },
   155	);
   156	```
   157	
   158	and receives an `EventSink` it writes to. The frontend choice (TUI vs stdout) and the journal are handled by the helper. `rhei-cli` only depends on `rhei-tui` for the event types and the helper; it does not see `ratatui` or `crossterm` directly.
   159	
   160	## CLI Changes
   161	
   162	Two new flags on `rhei run`:
   163	
   164	| Flag        | Description                                                              |
   165	|-------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------|
   166	| `--tui`     | Force TUI mode even when stdout is not detected as a TTY.                |
   167	| `--no-tui`  | Force plain stdout output even when stdout is a TTY.                     |
   168	
   169	The two flags are mutually exclusive. When neither is given, the frontend is auto-selected from `IsTerminal`.
   170	
   171	Existing flags (`--parallel`, `--dry-run`, `--continue-on-error`, `--agent`, etc.) retain their current semantics.
   172	
   173	## Backward Compatibility
   174	
   175	- Without `--tui` and in any non-TTY context, output matches the current line-oriented format byte-for-byte. Existing integration tests that grep stdout continue to pass.
   176	- The journal file is new. Runs that never produced a journal before will now produce one at `runtime/transitions.log`. This file is additive and does not alter plan state.
   177	- No existing flags change meaning.
   178	
   179	## Implementation Surface
   180	
   181	The engine refactor replaces direct `println!` sites in `run_agent_mode` (currently around `crates/rhei-cli/src/main.rs` lines 5007–5700) with `sink.emit(...)` calls. The call sites themselves do not change otherwise; the loop structure, task resolution, and spawn logic are preserved. The behavior of `StdoutSink` is defined to match today's formatted output, so this refactor is observably a no-op for all non-TTY users.
   182	
   183	## Dependencies
   184	
   185	The new `rhei-tui` crate adds:
   186	
   187	- `ratatui` — TUI widgets and layout.
   188	- `crossterm` — terminal backend, input handling.
   189	- `crossbeam-channel` — event channel between engine and render thread.
   190	
   191	All three are pure Rust with no C dependencies. `notify` is already a workspace dependency and is reused for log tailing.
   192	
   193	## Related Specifications
   194	
   195	- [Rhei Usage](rhei-usage.spec.md) — `rhei run` execution modes and roles.
   196	- [Agents Specification](rhei-agents.spec.md) — agent log capture and `runtime/logs/` layout.
   197	- [Program States Specification](rhei-programs.spec.md) — program execution and exit-code transitions.

